Based on the search results, here's what I found regarding SAE training objectives beyond L1 and evaluation methods in 2025-2026:

## Training Objectives Beyond L1

Recent methods have explored training SAEs with a combination of KL divergence and MSE loss to align training objectives more closely with evaluation objectives, with Braun et al. (2024) proposing "end-to-end" SAE training using KL+MSE loss throughout training. However, this method substantially increases computational cost, thus limiting practical applicability and widespread adoption by the field.

Chen et al. (2025) introduced a method leveraging low-rank adapters (LoRA) to fine-tune the underlying language model around pre-trained SAEs.

HierarchicalTopK is a novel activation mechanism and training objective that enables a single SAE to maintain interpretable features across a range of sparsity levels.

The superposition hypothesis implies that a single SAE latent may be pulled toward directions that blend multiple underlying features, particularly when the training objective (reconstruction fidelity plus sparsity) does not directly penalize such blending.

## Evaluation Methods Beyond L1

SAEBench (Karvonen et al., 2025) is a comprehensive suite of metrics beyond reconstruction accuracy.

The absence of appropriate metrics for interpretability evaluation is one of the main open problems with sparse autoencoders. Additionally, the L0 Pareto-front only partially predicts interpretability; optimizing proxy metrics may degrade true feature disentanglement.


