## Lee Sharkey and Apollo Research

Lee Sharkey co-founded Apollo Research and is most well-known for his early work on sparse autoencoders. He is currently an interpretability researcher at Goodfire.

## Sparse Autoencoders for Interpretability

Lee Sharkey contributed to a research paper on sparse autoencoders that addresses polysemanticity, where neurons appear to activate in multiple, semantically distinct contexts. The researchers used sparse autoencoders to reconstruct the internal activations of a language model.

## Recent Work (2025)

A recent paper titled "Interpretability in Parameter Space: Minimizing Mechanistic Description Length with Attribution-Based Parameter Decomposition" was authored by Dan Braun, Lucius Bushnaq, Stefan Heimersheim, Jake Mendel and Lee Sharkey. This work was discussed in a podcast episode from June 2025.

## Additional 2025 Research

Lee Sharkey at Apollo Research co-authored a paper titled "Sparse Autoencoders Do Not Find Canonical Units of Analysis," which examines limitations in how sparse autoencoders identify features in language models.


