## Overview

SAEBench is a comprehensive evaluation suite that measures SAE (sparse autoencoder) performance across eight diverse metrics, spanning interpretability, feature disentanglement and practical applications like unlearning.

## Authors and Publication

The benchmark was created by Adam Karvonen, Can Rager, Johnny Lin, Curt Tigges, Joseph Isaac Bloom, David Chanin, Yeu-Tong Lau, Eoin Farrell, Callum Stuart Mcdougall, Kola Ayonrinde, Demian Till, Matthew Wearden, Arthur Conmy, Samuel Marks, and Neel Nanda, published in the Proceedings of the 42nd International Conference on Machine Learning (PMLR 267:29223-29264, 2025).

## Key Contribution

The benchmark open-sources a suite of over 200 SAEs across seven recently proposed SAE architectures and training algorithms.

## Problem It Addresses

Most prior work evaluates progress using unsupervised proxy metrics with unclear practical relevance. The evaluation reveals that gains on proxy metrics do not reliably translate to better practical performance.

## Availability

You can compare 200+ SAEs of varying sparsity, dictionary size, architecture, and training time on Neuronpedia.


