Adam Karvonen, Can Rager, Johnny Lin, Curt Tigges, Joseph Isaac Bloom, and other collaborators published "SAEBench: A Comprehensive Benchmark for Sparse Autoencoders in Language Model Interpretability" at the 42nd International Conference on Machine Learning (PMLR 267:29223-29264) in 2025.

SAEBench is a comprehensive evaluation suite that measures sparse autoencoder (SAE) performance across eight diverse metrics, spanning interpretability, feature disentanglement and practical applications like unlearning. The research includes an open-sourced suite of over 200 SAEs across eight recently proposed SAE architectures and training algorithms.

The paper addresses an important gap in SAE research: most prior work evaluates progress using unsupervised proxy metrics with unclear practical relevance.


