# The World Inside Neural Networks

**Title:** The World Inside Neural Networks: How neural geometry will unlock understanding and control of AI

**Authors:** Atticus Geiger, Ekdeep Singh Lubana, Thomas Fel, Jack Merullo, Michael Jae Byun, Owen Lewis, Tom McGrath

**Date:** May 7, 2026

**Summary:** Neural networks develop internal geometric structures that mirror real-world relationships—like circular arrangements for months or smooth curves for spatial positions. By understanding these curved manifolds rather than treating representations as simple linear directions, researchers can develop more precise methods to interpret and control model behavior, moving beyond limitations of current approaches like sparse autoencoders.

---

## Relationship to SAEs and Mechanistic Interpretability

The work explicitly critiques sparse autoencoders' approach. The authors demonstrate that SAE features "tend to shatter manifolds into many small and apparently-unrelated pieces, obscuring the overarching semantic structure" that becomes visible when examining complete geometric forms. 

Their manifold-based framework represents a complementary mechanistic interpretability method that captures holistic conceptual structure rather than fragmenting it into isolated feature directions, enabling more robust interventions on neural network representations.

